title: Square du Vert-Galant
description:
Le niveau de la pointe du Vert-Galant montre l'ancien niveau de l'Île de la Cité.
En 1765 les berges arborées de saules et de tilleuls étaient occupées par un établissement de bains. En 1823 sa vogue était si grande qu'il abritait plus de 200 baignoires. En 1836 il devint la propriété de la Société des Trois Bains.

Origine du nom su square : le roi Henri IV de France avait pour surnom le "Vert galant".

title: Chapelle Expiatoire
description:
This is the place where Louis XVI and Maria Antoinette were brought and buried after their decapitation on the place the la Concorde. Its former name was Cimetière de Madeleine.
During the French Revolution it had been a cemetery. Many victims of the guillotine were
buried there. It is also a mass grave (approx. 600 persons) of the Swiss Guards who were slaughtered after the storming of the Tuileries Palace on the 10th august 1792.
Louis brother XVIII. built in the early 1800 a chapel to honor the victims of the French terror.

urlhtml: Notre-Dame-des-Victoires (basilique) -Marian sanctuary and place of pilgrimage in Paris
title: Notre-Dame-des-Victoires (basilique)  -Marian sanctuary and place of pilgrimage in Paris
description: Situated on the elegant little square of Petits-Pères, this church is the only vestige of the Eglise des Augustins for which Louis XIII laid the first stone in 1629. The name of the church commemorated the King's victories, notably that of the siege of La Rochelle. The church was not completed until 1740. From 1795 to 1809, the Bourse (stock exchange) established itself in the church. The basilica is a highly popular place of pilgrimage as is demonstrated by the numerous ex voto (according to prayer) plaques.

title: Pont des Arts
description: The Pont des Arts (or the Pedestrian Bridge) is a bridge in Paris which crosses Seine River. It links the Institut de France and the central square (cour carrée) of the palais du Louvre (which had been termed the "Palais des Arts" under the First French Empire).
